Solution $$\begin{aligned}\sum_{j=3}^{\infty} \frac{j}{\lfloor \frac j2\rfloor !}&= 3+\sum_{k=2}^{\infty} \frac{2k}{k!}+\frac{2k+1}{k!}
\\ &= 3+4\sum_{k=2}^{\infty} \frac{1}{(k 1)!} + \sum_{k=2}^{\infty} \frac 1{k!}
\\ &= 3+4(e 1)+(e 2) = \boxed{5e 3}
\end{aligned}$$

Let $\overline{ab}=x \overline{cd}=y $ 

 Then we have 
 \begin{align*}
\overline{abcd} = (\overline{ab})^2 + (\overline{cd})^2 &\implies 100x+y=x^2+y^2 \\
&\implies 100x x^2=y^2 y \\
&\implies x(100 x)=y^2 y \end{align*} By symmetry if there is some pair $(x_0 y_0)$ of positive integers that satisfy this equation then $(100 x_0 y_0)$ will also satisfy it Since we are given that $(x y)=(88 33)$ works we can then conclude that $(12 33)$ also works so the answer is $\boxed{1233} $ $\square$ 

 Remark Indeed we have 
 \begin{align*}
12^2+33^2 &= 144+1089 \\
&= 1233 \end{align*}

First note that we can split the region of interest into two different circular segments The area of the circular segment that is part of the circle centered at $A$ is 
 \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{6} \cdot 1^2 \cdot \pi \frac{(\sqrt{3})^2 \cdot \sqrt{3}}{4} &= \frac{\pi}{6} \cdot 1 \frac{3\cdot\sqrt{3}}{4} \\
&= \frac{\pi}{6} \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{4} \end{align*} and the area of the circular segment that is part of the circle centered at $D$ is 
 \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{3} \cdot 1^2 \cdot \pi \frac{1}{2} \cdot 1^2 \cdot \sin(120^\circ) &= \frac{\pi}{3} \cdot 1 \frac{1}{2} \cdot 1 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
&= \frac{\pi}{3} \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \end{align*} so the answer is 
 \begin{align*}
\left(\frac{\pi}{6} \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{4}\right)+\left(\frac{\pi}{3} \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}\right) &= \boxed{\frac{5\pi}{6} \sqrt{3}} \end{align*} $\square$

